@node bugs "Known Bugs and common problems"
In certain conditions when there are a lot of different weather phonomena being observed, Wet may report none.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} This is due to a bug in dos.library v50+; fixed in OS4.1u1. (severity: low,rare)

Wet gives error "Unable to resolve IP address" when it is placed in WBStartUp, but updates the weather correctly when Update is clicked later.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} Add DELAY=n (where n is the number of seconds to wait) to Wet's tooltypes.

The error "no data available" appears.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} This is due to no data being available for the current ICAO code.  Sometimes this error will not reappear if you try another update, but usually it is persistent.  Try another nearby ICAO code from the pop-up gadget next to the find button.

One digit is cut off of the date/time display in the GUI.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} The gadget sizes to the same as the largest cycle gadget below it needs.  I can't force it any larger due to a bug in the string gadget class. (I believe this has already been fixed;  Severity: low)

Wet's docky icon multiples when AmiDock is minimised.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} Fixed in OS4; 4.1u1 introduces the opposite problem where the icon disappears when unminimised. (Severity: low)

Wet's docky icon does not appear when Wet is in WBStartUp under OS4.1u1.
@{b}Solution:@{ub} Workaround in Wet 5.5 is to add tooltype STARTUPDELAY=1 (Severity: low)

See also the bugtracker at http://www.unsatisfactorysoftware.co.uk/bugs
@endnode

@node icons "Icon naming"
The icons must all be in the theme directory (specified by the THEME tooltype) in the data path pointed to by the DATA tooltype.  If Wet can't find an icon it can use, it won't display any AppIcon at all.

Wet searches the following directories, starting from the deepest directory level and traversing to higher levels if it doesn't find anything suitable:
<data path>/<theme>/<weather condition>/<intensity>

The icons are always (with exceptions listed below) numbered with a value relating to the amount of cloud cover from 0-7 - detailed below.  If Wet determines that it is currently night time, it will first try to open an icon appended with "_n" (and the moon phase initially if v6.1+, see below).  If Wet can't find a file with the correct number, it will reduce the value until it gets to 0 (again, appending "_n" first if it is overnight).  If it still hasn't found a suitable icon, it will drop down one directory level and start again.  The weather condition directories are named with two character IDs listed below.

If Wet fails to find an icon by the time it has reached cloud level 1, it will start searching for the wind strength (beaufort scale) in a subdirectory called "wind".  If it does not find anything here, it will finish searching for 1.info and 0.info in the root of the data path.

Therefore the default icon if no other is found, should be called 0.info and be placed in the root of the theme path.  This indicates "sunny" (or at least "clear" for night time) conditions.  Likewise if you only have one icon in a condition directory, it should also be called 0.info.

The overlaid icons are slightly different as they are only loaded if the exact filename is found (Wet will not search for another suitable icon if the requested one is not found, with the exception of reverting to the daytime icon if the nighttime version is not available).  These @{b}must@{ub} be smaller than the main icon.  Please note that versions prior to v5, and the 68k version when AfA icon.library is not installed, require that icons and overlays do not exceed a total of 256 colours for best results, and 32-bit icons with overlays will not work in those configurations or with PowerIcons. 

You can disable the overlays for particular main icons with the tooltype NOOVERLAY.  This has four possible options (which can be combined with the vertical bar): WIND, MOON, CLOUD, INTENSITY.  The quickest way to disable all overlays is to delete the corresponding icons from Wet's data directory.

Wet will check for the following mini icons:
<data path>/<theme>/mini/<intensity>
<data path>/<theme>/mini/wind/<beaufort>
<data path>/<theme>/mini/cld/<cloud cover>
<data path>/<theme>/mini/moon/<moon phase>  (v6.1+)

The final icon in the theme directory is called "project" and is only used when "Save as" is selected from the "Project" menu.

You can specify where the mini icon should be overlaid by adding the tooltypes XOFFSET and YOFFSET to the mini icon's tooltypes.  This is an integer, with positive values specifying an offset from the left or top, and negative values specifying an offset from the right or bottom.  The default is to put the intensity icon in the bottom-right, the cloud cover in the bottom-left and the wind in the top-left.

@{b}Intensities@{ub}
@{fg fill}Vicinity@{fg text} (weather is occuring nearby)
@{fg fill}Light@{fg text}
@{fg fill}Moderate@{fg text}
@{fg fill}Heavy@{fg text}

@{b}Cloud Cover@{ub}
@{fg fill}0@{fg text}  None
@{fg fill}1@{fg text}  None below 12000 feet (no clouds detected)
@{fg fill}2@{fg text}  None below 5000 feet (clouds above 5000ft are present)
@{fg fill}3@{fg text}  1/8 - 2/8 cover
@{fg fill}4@{fg text}  3/8 - 4/8 cover
@{fg fill}5@{fg text}  5/8 - 7/8 cover
@{fg fill}6@{fg text}  8/8 cover
@{fg fill}7@{fg text}  8/8 cover (indeterminable ceiling)

@{b}Moon Phases@{ub} (v6.1)
These are appended to the end of night-time icons, eg. 0_n4.info will be tried before 0_n.info, and also as mini icons.  To get moon phase mini icons showing only on night-time icons, ensure only _n versions are present, eg mini/moon/3_n.info

@{fg fill}0@{fg text}  New Moon
@{fg fill}1@{fg text}  Waxing Crescent
@{fg fill}2@{fg text}  First Quarter
@{fg fill}3@{fg text}  Waxing Gibbous
@{fg fill}4@{fg text}  Full Moon
@{fg fill}5@{fg text}  Waning Gibbous
@{fg fill}6@{fg text}  Third Quarter
@{fg fill}7@{fg text}  Waning Crescent

@{b}Conditions@{ub}
@{fg fill}IC@{fg text} Ice Crystals
@{fg fill}UP@{fg text} Unknown Precipitation
@{fg fill}PL@{fg text} Ice Pellets
@{fg fill}SN@{fg text} Snow
@{fg fill}GR@{fg text} Hail
@{fg fill}SG@{fg text} Snow Grains
@{fg fill}GS@{fg text} Small Hailstones
@{fg fill}DZ@{fg text} Drizzle
@{fg fill}RA@{fg text} Rain
@{fg fill}TS@{fg text} Thunderstorm
@{fg fill}SH@{fg text} Showers
@{fg fill}BR@{fg text} Mist
@{fg fill}FU@{fg text} Smoke
@{fg fill}HZ@{fg text} Haze
@{fg fill}VA@{fg text} Volcanic Ash
@{fg fill}PY@{fg text} Spray
@{fg fill}DU@{fg text} Dust
@{fg fill}SA@{fg text} Sand
@{fg fill}FG@{fg text} Fog
@{fg fill}SQ@{fg text} Squalls
@{fg fill}FC@{fg text} Funnel Cloud*
@{fg fill}SS@{fg text} Sandstorm
@{fg fill}DS@{fg text} Dust Storm
@{fg fill}PO@{fg text} Dust Whirl or Sand Whirl

* fc/heavy is classed as a tornado or water spout.  Wet does not currently distinguish between the two, although you can find out which it is by selecting Project=>Remarks.

@{b}Beaufort Scale@{ub}
The beaufort scale ranges from 0 (calm) to 12 (hurricane).  v6.1 extends this with the Saffir-Simpson hurricane scale as pseudo-Beaufort values 13 (cat 2) - 16 (cat 5).
@endnode

@node nsdcccc "nsd_cccc.txt"
You can update the site information file by using the Execute ARexx menu item and selecting the update_sites.rexx script.  This requires WGet (available on OS4Depot) to be in your path (eg. C:), and after a few seconds will report that the file has been updated.

Alternatively, you can update the file manually by visiting http://weather.noaa.gov/tg/site.shtml and downloading one of the "keyed by location indicator" files from the links towards the bottom of the page.

@{b}Important Note@{ub}
Do not download the PKZipped version; this dates back to 2003 and has errors in the file.

Generally any minor errors in this file can be skipped over by using "Continue" in Grim Reaper.  Wet does not yet check for correct data within this file, so if you are unsure please keep using the original file.

@endnode

@node arexx "ARexx Port"
Wet's ARexx port is called "WET.1" and implements the following commands.  The lowest internal version number of Wet required for each command is given in brackets.  You can get and check this from ARexx by calling the VERSION command.

@{"CONVERT  " link rx_convert} (3.1)
@{"DEGTODEC " link rx_degtodec} (5.3)
@{"FINDICAO " link rx_findicao} (4.9)
@{"GETUNIT  " link rx_getunit} (3.1)
@{"GETVALUE " link rx_getvalue} (3.1)
@{"HEATINDEX" link rx_heatindex} (5.3)
@{"HUMIDITY " link rx_humidity} (3.10)
@{"MOONPHASE" link rx_phase} (6.1)
@{"REQUEST  " link rx_request} (5.3)
@{"SITEINFO " link rx_siteinfo} (3.1)
@{"SUNSET   " link rx_sunset} (3.4)
@{"UPDATE   " link rx_update} (3.4)
@{"VERSION  " link rx_version} (3.1)
@{"WINDCHILL" link rx_windchill} (5.2)

The following are only of interest to Wet @{"plugins" link plugins} (added in v6.1):
@{"POSTMETAR" link rx_postmetar}
@{"UPDATEGUI" link rx_updategui}

There are some scripts that the installer installs in the REXX: directory.  Information regarding these can normally be found in the respective file.
@endnode

@node rx_convert "Convert"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

CONVERT VALUE/A,FROM/A,TO/A

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

VALUE: Value to convert
FROM:  Unit to convert from (see below)
TO:    Unit to convert to (see below)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Converted value

@{b}Details@{ub}

CONVERT converts VALUE from unit FROM to unit TO, and returns the converted value in RESULT to two decimal places.

FROM and TO can be any of the following, but must both be of the same type.  If they are not the same type, this command will return the value passed to it.

DEGC    = Degrees Celsius/Centigrade (Temperature)
DEGF    = Degrees Fahrenheit (Temperature)
KTS     = Knots (Speed)
MPS     = Metres per second (Speed)
KMH     = Kilometres per hour (Speed)
MPH     = Miles per hour (Speed)
BEAU    = Beaufort scale (Speed)
HPA     = Hectopascals/Millibars (Pressure)
INHG    = Inches of mercury (Pressure)
METRES  = Metres (Distance)
FEET    = Feet (Distance)
MILES   = Miles (Distance)
KM      = Kilometres (Distance)
DEGREES = Degrees (Direction) (4.23)
COMPASS = Compass points (numeric range 0-15 where 0=N, 1=NNE etc) (Direction) (4.23)
GRID    = Logically the same as degrees but cannot be mapped to compass points - may be returned by GETUNIT but will not be accepted by CONVERT.  If you need to convert GRID, tell CONVERT that the unit is DEGREES. (Direction) (4.23)
@endnode

@node rx_degtodec "DegToDec"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

DEGTODEC DEG/A/N,MIN/A/N,SEC/A/N,HEM

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DEG: Degrees value of latitude/longitude
MIN: Minutes value of latitude/longitude
SEC: Seconds value of latitude/longitude
HEM: Hemisphere - N, E, S or W.

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Latitude/longitude to 4 decimal places.

@{b}Details@{ub}

Converts the latitude or longitude specified from DMS notation to decimal form.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

This is a one-way conversion as Wet's ARexx commands require the location in decimal format.  If you want to convert from decimal to DMS, there is an ARexx script included in Wet's distribution archive that shows how to do this.
@endnode

@node rx_findicao "FINDICAO"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

FINDICAO LATITUDE/A LONGITUDE/A

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

LATITUDE:  in decimal form
LONGITUDE: in decimal form

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Four character ICAO code
RC: Non-zero if an error occured

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command returns the ICAO code of the site closest to the location specified by the latitude and longitude arguments.

@endnode


@node rx_getunit "GETUNIT"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

GETUNIT DATA/A

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DATA: Data source to get a unit for (see @{"GETVALUE" link rx_getvalue} for possible values)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Unit, see @{"CONVERT" link rx_convert} for possible values.
RC: 1 if an error occured.

@{b}Details@{ub}

GETUNIT gets the units associated with a particular value.  This value is the one associated with data DATA.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* This code will return either DEGC or DEGF depending on user's current settings. */
options results
address wet
getunit temp
say result

@endnode

@node rx_getvalue "GETVALUE"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

GETVALUE DATA/A

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DATA: Data source to get a value for (see below)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value
RC: 1 if an error occured

@{b}Details@{ub}

GETVALUE gets the value of a particular piece of data.

DATA can be one of the following:

DATAPATH      = Path to Wet's data files (3.11)
DATE          = Date of last observation, in dd/mm/yyyy (4.6)
DEWPOINT      = Dew Point
LOCWEATHER    = Localised human-readable weather string
PLUGINSITE    = Site code for @{"plug-in use only" link plugins}, other scripts should use SITE (6.1)
PRESSURE      = Pressure
SITE          = Four character site code (can be passed to @{"SITEINFO" link rx_siteinfo})
TEMP          = Temperature
THEME         = Icon theme name (5.1)
TIME          = Time of last observation, in hh:mm (4.6)
VISIBILITY    = Visibility distance
WEATHER       = Current most significant conditions, as a two character ID (see @{"icon naming" link icons} for a list)
WINDDIRECTION = Wind direction (will return -1 if wind is variable)
WINDSPEED     = Wind speed


@{b}Example@{ub}

/* This code will return the current temperature */
options results
address wet
getvalue temp
say result

@endnode

@node rx_heatindex "HEATINDEX"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

HEATINDEX HUMIDITY/A,TEMP/A,TYPE

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

HUMIDITY:  Relative humidity
TEMP:      Temperature in degrees celsius (DEGC)
TYPE:      HEATINDEX or HUMIDEX

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value

@{b}Details@{ub}

HEATINDEX calculates the heat index or humidex ("feels like") temperature for a given temperature and relative humidity.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* Calculate heat index and humidex for current values */

options results
address wet.1

/* Get dew point in dp and ensure it is in the correct units */
getvalue dewpoint
dp = result
getunit dewpoint
dpu = result
convert dp dpu DEGC
dp = result

/* Get temperature in temp and convert to Celsius if necessary */
getvalue temp
temp = result
getunit temp
tempu = result
convert temp tempu DEGC
temp = result

/* Calculate humidity and put it in rh */
humidity dp temp REL
rh = result

/* Calculate wind chill and display the output */
heatindex rh temp HEATINDEX
say "Heat Index =" result
heatindex rh temp HUMIDEX
say "Humidex =" result
@endnode

@node rx_humidity "HUMIDITY"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

HUMIDITY DEWPOINT/A,PRES=TEMP/A,TYPE

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DEWPOINT:  Dew point temperature in degrees celsius (DEGC)
PRES=TEMP: Pressure in HectoPascals/millibars (HPA) or temperature in DEGC (see below)
TYPE:      See below

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value

@{b}Details@{ub}

HUMIDITY calculates the humidity for a given dewpoint and temperature/pressure.

TYPE can be one of the following:

REL = Relative humidity.  You must supply temperature in the second argument.  Result is given as a percentage value.

ABS = Absolute humidity.  You must supply temperature in the second argument.  Result is given in g/mł (grams per cubic metre)

SPC = Specific humidity.  You must supply pressure in the second argument.  Result is given in g/kg (grams per kilogram)

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* Calculate humidity for current values */

options results
address wet

/* Get dew point in dp and ensure it is in the correct units */
getvalue dewpoint
dp = result
getunit dewpoint
dpu = result
convert dp dpu DEGC
dp = result

/* Get temperature in temp and convert to Celsius if necessary */
getvalue temp
temp = result
getunit temp
tempu = result
convert temp tempu DEGC
temp = result

/* Get pressure in pres and convert to hPa */
getvalue pressure
pres = result
getunit pressure
presu = result
convert pres presu HPA
pres = result

/* Calculate humidity and display the output */
humidity dp temp REL
say "Relative humidity =" result "%"
humidity dp temp ABS
say "Absolute humidity =" result "g/mł"
humidity dp pres SPC
say "Specific humidity =" result "g/kg"
@endnode

@node rx_phase "MOONPHASE"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

MOONPHASE DAY/A/N,MONTH/A/N,YEAR/A/N

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DAY, MONTH, YEAR: Date to retrieve moon phase for.

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Moon phase 0-7
Where 0 is "new moon" and 4 is "full moon".
See table in @{"icon naming" link icons} for more details.

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command calculates the approximate phase of the moon for a particular date.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* Prints the moon phase value for 20th January 2010 */

address wet.1
options results
MOONPHASE 20 1 2010
say result
@endnode

@node rx_request "REQUEST"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

REQUEST TEXT/A,BUTTONS,STRING/S

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

TEXT:    Text for the main body of the requester
BUTTONS: Button text, seperated with vertical bar |
STRING:  String requester

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command displays a requester with the TEXT and BUTTONS specified.  If the STRING switch is used, it will display a requester with a string gadget and the buttons "OK" and "Cancel" (localised).

The RESULT variable will hold either the number of the button pressed (right-hand button is 0, left-hand button and other buttons start counting from 1), or the string the user entered.  If the string requester is cancelled, RESULT will hold an empty string.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* Asks for the user's name and says hello */

address wet.1
options results
request '"What is your name?"' STRING
request '"Hello' result ||'" "Goodbye"'
@endnode


@node rx_siteinfo "SITEINFO"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

SITEINFO ICAO/A,VALUE/A

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

ICAO:  Four character ICAO ID
VALUE: Information to return

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Requested data
RC: 1 if an error occured

@{b}Details@{ub}

SITEINFO gets information for the site specified by ICAO.

VALUE can be one of the following:

NAME      = Site name
COUNTRY   = Country site is based in
LATITUDE  = Latitude of site in decimal form (3.4)
LONGITUDE = Longitude of site in decimal form (3.4) 

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* This code will return the name of the current site */
options results
address wet
getvalue site
icao = result
siteinfo icao name
say result
@endnode

@node rx_sunset "SUNSET"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

SUNSET LATITUDE/A,LONGITUDE/A,DAY/A,MONTH/A,YEAR/A,RISE/S,ZENITH   (3.4)

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

LATITUDE:  Latitude, in decimal form
LONGITUDE: Longitude, in decimal form
DAY:       Day of month, 1-31
MONTH:     Month, 1-12
YEAR:      Year, full format (eg, 2005 not 05)
RISE:      Specify to get sunrise time instead of sunset
ZENITH:    Sun's angle above the horizon (see below)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Time as 24-hour clock, colon separated.

@{b}Details@{ub}

SUNSET gets the sunset or sunrise time for a specified location, in local time.

ZENITH can be one of the following:

OFFICIAL     = 90°50'
CIVIL        = 96°
NAUTICAL     = 102°
ASTRONOMICAL = 108°

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Prior to version 5.3, the default for ZENITH if not specified was OFFICIAL.
In v5.3 this was changed to be the user's current setting within Wet.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* This code will return "civil" sunset and sunrise time for the current site */
options results
address wet
/* Get site ICAO code */
getvalue site
icao = result
/* Get latitude and longitude of current site */
siteinfo icao latitude
lati = result
siteinfo icao longitude
longi = result
/* Get and split the current date */
date = date('s')
year = substr(date,1,4)
month = substr(date,5,2)
day = substr(date,7,2)
/* Get sunset time */
sunset lati longi day month year CIVIL
say "Sunset at" result
/* Get sunrise time */
sunset lati longi day month year CIVIL RISE
say "Sunrise at" result
@endnode

@node rx_update "UPDATE"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

UPDATE ICAO/A  (3.4)

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

ICAO:  Four character ICAO ID

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

None.

@{b}Details@{ub}

UPDATE gets the weather for the requested ICAO code and updates the @{i}internal values only@{ui}.  Wet GUI and AppIcon remain unchanged, but the new values can be queried with ARexx.  Since 6.1 the GUI can be updated with @{"UPDATEGUI" link rx_updategui}.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The new values obtained will be valid until Wet gets new data either automatically or due to the user or another ARexx script updating the information.  If you query a site other than the one currently in use, it is possible that the values will be overwritten before you have finished with them.  It is also possible that Wet will not return information from another site due to safeguards in place to stop unnecessary server traffic.

Therefore, it is strongly recommended to only use this function to update values for the current ICAO code, using something like the below code:

/* Update current weather information for ARexx use only */
options results
address wet

getvalue site
icao=result
update icao
@endnode

@node rx_version "VERSION"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

VERSION

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

none

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Internal version number

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command returns the internal version number of Wet.  This is in standard Amiga version number format, therefore the numbers before and after the dot must be treated as seperate values.

@endnode

@node rx_windchill "WINDCHILL"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

WINDCHILL TEMP/A,WINDSPEED/A,TYPE

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

TEMP:      Temperature in degrees celsius (DEGC)
WINDSPEED: Wind speed in km/h (KMH)
TYPE:      OLD (Steadman algorithm) or NEW (JAG/TI)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value

@{b}Details@{ub}

WINDCHILL calculates the wind chill ("feels like") temperature for a given temperature and wind speed.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Prior to v5.3, the default method was NEW (JAG/TI).  From v5.3 the default is that selected by the user.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* Calculate wind chill for current values */

options results
address wet

/* Get wind speed and ensure it is in the correct units */
getvalue windspeed
ws = result
getunit windspeed
wsu = result
convert ws wsu KMH
ws = result

/* Get temperature in temp and convert to Celsius if necessary */
getvalue temp
temp = result
getunit temp
tempu = result
convert temp tempu DEGC
temp = result

/* Calculate wind chill and display the output */
windchill temp ws
say "Wind chill =" result
@endnode

@remark ------ PLUGINS -------

@node plugins "Plug-ins"
Wet's plug-in system is ARexx based.  To activate, the user must specify the plugin filename in their tooltypes, eg:
USEPLUGIN=example.wet_plugin

It is recommended that any plug-in Installer will make this change (see @{"installer example" link plugin_installer})

The plug-in itself is very simple and comprises of several @{"SETVALUE" link rx_setvalue} commands followed by @{"UPDATEGUI" link rx_updategui}.

The user's site code can also be obtained with @{"GETVALUE" link rx_getvalue} PLUGINSITE (in plugin mode this can be any combination of letters and numbers up to 100 characters in length).

An example is @{"example.wet_plugin" link ARexx/example.wet_plugin/Main} found in the ARexx dir of the archive, or installed along with the other ARexx scripts in REXX:

@endnode

@node plugin_installer
; This little example only set the USEPLUGIN tooltype, it does not copy any files.

(set #plugin "example.wet_plugin")

(set #programdir (getenv "AppPaths/Wet"))

(if (= #programdir "")
	(
		(set #programdir
			(askdir
    			(prompt "Where is your Wet executable?")
        		(help @askdir-help)
        		(default "SYS:WBStartUp")
			)
		)
	)
)

(tooltype
	(prompt "Modifying theme in tooltypes")
	(help @tooltype-help)
	(dest (tackon #programdir "Wet"))
	(settooltype "USEPLUGIN" #plugin)
)

@endnode

@node rx_postmetar "POSTMETAR"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

POSTMETAR METAR/A/F

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

A properly-formed METAR string.

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RC set to 5 if the METAR could not be decoded.

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command decodes a metar and sets weather values internally.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

See @{"plugins" link plugins} for more information. 
@endnode

@node rx_setvalue "SETVALUE"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

SETVALUE DATA/A,VALUE/A,UNITS

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

DATA: Data source to get a value for (see below)
VALUE: Value to set that data to
UNITS: Units the value is in (if applicable, see @{"CONVERT" link rx_convert} for a list)

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

RESULT: Value
RC: 1 if an error occured

@{b}Details@{ub}

GETVALUE gets the value of a particular piece of data.

DATA can be one of the following:

CLOUDS        = Cloud cover (0-4, where 0 is clear skies)
CLOUDHEIGHT   = Cloud height
DEWPOINT      = Dew Point
PRESSURE      = Pressure
SITELOCATION  = Location of site (usually country)
SITENAME      = Site name (usually town)
TEMP          = Temperature
VISIBILITY    = Visibility distance
WEATHER       = Current weather as a two character ID in METAR format (ses below)
WINDDIRECTION = Wind direction
WINDSPEED     = Wind speed

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Weather is specified in METAR format.  This consists of several characters representing Intensity, Descriptor and Phenomena.  The AmigaOS pattern looks like this:
(+|-|VC|%)(TS|BL|BC|PR|DR|FZ|MI|SH|%)#(IC|UP|PL|SN|GR|SG|GS|DZ|RA|BR|FU|HZ|VA|PY|DU|FG|SA|SQ|FC|SS|DS|PO|NSW)

This is perhaps quite daunting.  In simple terms, weather can be described as a two character ID (see @{"icon naming" link icons} for a list), optionally prepended by + (heavy) or - (light).  NSW can be used if no significant weather is present.

eg. +SN is heavy snow.

Full details can be found at http://atmo.tamu.edu/class/METAR/metar-pg9-ww.html

See @{"plugins" link plugins} for more information about SETVALUE and plugins.

@{b}Example@{ub}

/* This code will set the current temperature to 10°C*/
setvalue temp "10 DEGC"
@endnode

@node rx_updategui "UPDATEGUI"
@toc arexx
@{b}Template@{ub}

UPDATEGUI

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

None.

@{b}Outputs@{ub}

None.

@{b}Details@{ub}

This command updates Wet's display, icon(s), env-vars, sends a Ringhio notification and calls the user's @{"AUTORUNAREXX" link tooltypes} script.

It @{b}must@{ub} be run by plugins after they have finished setting values.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

See @{"plugins" link plugins} for more information.
@endnode
